2. In this lab, all three tasks involved taking existing analysis and presenting it interactively. What does Leaflet add beyond what `tmap` could do? And conversely, what did you give up by switching to Leaflet? Consider both technical and cartographic dimensions.

Leaflet provides a lot more interactivability compared to tmap. tmap had the view mode, which I really liked, where I could zoom or move the map around like I can in Leaflet. I think one of the biggest features about leaflet that I liked was the ability to toggle between maps. This was interactive and meaningful. In tmap, I can layer maps to make a more complex map, or if I want two maps side-by-side I can do that. But in leaflet I can switch between two maps in the exact same spot, which I think can be very useful in some situations. The other thing is the popups and labels. I think these features provide a lot of opportunities that tmap doesn't have. But map interaction isn't always necessary. tmap might be better for having an inset map just because you're looking closely at the map with the relavent data, but you're being shown the context of the area this is from, and that can tell the reader what they need to know and there is no reason for exploration in an interactive map. tmap would be better for making maps to publish in a reading whereas leaflet is good for use in a database or app.

3. Describe the "one thing" you chose to add to your map in Task 3. What did you implement, why is it applicable to your specific map, and how does it change the user's experience compared to a static version?

I implemented a popup to show the population density of my choropleth map. I chose this way to show this information as using a legend doesn't show the small numbers. This would have been a problem on a legend in a static map as well. Using the popup in leaflet allowed me to show the full numbers so that each county's values could be differentiated. But if the user doesn't care to see the numbers, they don't have to focus on it. This is applicable to this map because population density plays a role in land cover, so while abserving which counties have a more dense population than others might be enough to answer questions, seeing the proportion of population to area may be beneficial depending on the observer's intention.

