## Bonus (+20 points)

Extend your Task 2 LISA map to include a **synchronized side-by-side view**: the LISA quadrant map on one side and the underlying variable choropleth (from Task 1 or your Lab 3 variable) on the other. The `leafsync` package provides `sync()` for this purpose.

The two maps should share the same extent and zoom level. When you pan or zoom one, the other follows. Add a brief comment explaining what analytical value this comparison provides.

```{r bonus, echo=TRUE, message=TRUE}
#preparing for mapping of my variable from task 2
local.states3 <- sf::st_transform(local.states2, 4326)

min(local.states2$f21prop, na.rm = TRUE)
max(local.states2$f21prop, na.rm = TRUE)

breaksb <- seq(min(0), max(0.09331104), length.out = 5)

palbonus <- colorBin(palette = "RdPu", domain = local.states2$f21prop, bins = breaksb)

# new map
lisa_map <- leaflet(local.states3) %>% 
  setView(lng = -80, lat = 38, zoom = 5) %>% 
  addTiles() %>%
  addPolygons(., fillColor = ~palbonus(local.states3$f21prop), 
    weight = 1, color = "black", fillOpacity = 0.9) %>%
  addLegend(position = "bottomright", pal = palbonus, values =  palbonus, title = "Proportion of females age 20-24")
lisa_map

# quadrant map
choro <- leaflet(counties_lisa) %>% addTiles() %>% 
  setView(lng = -80, lat = 38, zoom = 5) %>% 
  addPolygons(
    fillColor   = ~pal_lisa(quadrant),
    fillOpacity = 0.8,
    color       = "black",
    weight      = 1,
    popup = ~paste0(sprintf("%.3f", pval))) %>%
  addLegend(position = "bottomright", pal = pal_lisa, values = counties_lisa$quadrant, title = "Moran's I Quadrant")
choro

#attempting bonus

library(leafsync)

sync(lisa_map, choro)


```

Looking at maps side-by-side like this can provide a similar benefit to toggling between maps, but without having to click back and forth. The special thing about this is that when you zoom on one side, it zooms on the other and this can help the observer find patterns more quickly. For example, looking at the underlying variable map on the left, my eye goes to the biggest polygon with the darkest pink. I can zoom in, or hover my mouse over this county, and very quickly see which LISA quadrant this county was.

